7 Sec. 17012a. (1) Beginning 18 months after the effective date
8 of the amendatory act that added this section, the board may grant
9 a temporary license to engage in the practice of medicine to an
10 applicant if the applicant demonstrates all of the following to the
11 board:
12 (a) The applicant has completed the requirements for a degree
13 in medicine at a medical school that is located outside the United
14 States or Canada and that is listed in the World Directory of
15 Medical Schools, a directory maintained by the World Federation for
16 Medical Education and the Foundation for Advancement of
17 International Medical Education and Research, and that meets or
18 exceeds the standards of medical schools located in the United
19 States or Canada, as determined by the board.
20 (b) The applicant was authorized to practice medicine in a
21 country other than the United States or Canada and practiced
22 medicine in that country for not less than 3 years within the 8
23 years immediately preceding the date of the application for
24 temporary licensure under this section.
25 (c) The applicant has a certification issued by the
26 Educational Commission for Foreign Medical Graduates or an
27 equivalent certification as determined by the board. The board may
28 waive the certification requirement described in this subdivision
29 if the applicant demonstrates to the satisfaction of the board that
EMR H03792'25 (H-3) jpg0bq

3
1 the applicant is unable to obtain the required documentation from a
2 noncooperating country.
3 (d) The applicant has successfully completed step 1 and step 2
4 of the United States Medical Licensing Examination or an equivalent
5 medical licensure examination as determined by the board.
6 (e) Subject to subsection (2), the applicant has entered into
7 an agreement with a participating facility or practice for full-
8 time employment under the supervision of a physician who is fully
9 licensed under this part.
10 (f) The applicant meets any other requirement established by
11 the board.
12 (2) The agreement required under subsection (1) must require
13 the participating facility or practice to assess and evaluate the
14 applicant's nonclinical skills and other skills that the board
15 considers appropriate to the practice of medicine in this state,
16 according to evaluation criteria developed or approved by the
17 board, and to provide the department, on request, with a letter
18 from the physician described in subsection (1)(e) attesting to the
19 applicant's competence to engage in the practice of medicine in
20 this state. An applicant seeking a temporary license under this
21 section shall obtain a temporary license before beginning the
22 supervised employment experience. A temporary license granted under
23 this section is valid for 2 years and is renewable only once.
24 (3) The board may grant a limited license to engage in the
25 practice of medicine to an applicant who holds a temporary license
26 under subsection (1) if the applicant demonstrates all of the
27 following to the board:
28 (a) The applicant has held the temporary license for not less
29 than 2 years.
EMR H03792'25 (H-3) jpg0bq

4
1 (b) The applicant has successfully completed step 3 of the
2 United States Medical Licensing Examination or an equivalent
3 medical licensure examination as determined by the board.
4 (c) The applicant has the nonclinical and other skills that
5 the board considers appropriate to the practice of medicine in this
6 state, based on an assessment and evaluation of the applicant under
7 subsection (2) by a participating facility or practice, and a
8 letter of recommendation from the physician described in subsection
9 (1)(e).
10 (d) The applicant is not subject to any disciplinary action or
11 pending investigations.
12 (4) An individual who is granted a limited license under
13 subsection (3) may engage in the practice of medicine without the
14 supervision of a physician who is fully licensed under this part,
15 but the individual shall confine the individual's practice to a
16 medically underserved area of this state. A limited license that is
17 granted under this section is valid for 2 years and is renewable
18 only once.
19 (5) This section does not require new or additional third-
20 party reimbursement or mandated worker's compensation benefits for
21 services rendered by an individual who is licensed under this
22 section.
23 (6) As used in this section:
24 (a) "Medically underserved area of this state" means an area
25 of this state that is a primary care health professional shortage
26 area, as determined by the Health Resources and Services
27 Administration of the United States Department of Health and Human
28 Services.
29 (b) "Participating facility or practice" means a federally
EMR H03792'25 (H-3) jpg0bq

5
1 qualified health center, a hospital licensed under article 17, or
2 another facility that is approved by the board, or a group practice
3 of 4 or more physicians.
4 Sec. 17012b. (1) The department shall collect and maintain all
5 of the following information for purposes of section 17012a:
6 (a) The number of applicants for a temporary license and a
7 limited license.
8 (b) The number of applicants who are denied a temporary
9 license or a limited license.
10 (c) The number of individuals who are granted a temporary
11 license or limited license.
12 (d) The number of individuals who are granted a license under
13 section 17031(2)(b).
14 (2) The department shall submit an annual report containing
15 the information required under subsection (1) to the senate and
16 house of representatives standing committees on health policy. The
17 report required under this subsection may also include specific
18 recommendations for any changes to section 17012a that the
19 department considers necessary or appropriate.
20 Sec. 17031. (1) Except as provided in subsection (2), an
21 applicant, in addition to completing the requirements for the
22 degree in medicine, shall complete a period of postgraduate
23 education to attain proficiency in the practice of the profession,
24 as prescribed by the board in rules, as a condition for more than
25 limited or temporary licensure.
26 (2) The board may grant a full license to practice medicine to
27 an applicant who has completed the requirements for a degree in
28 medicine at a medical school located outside the United States or
29 Canada if, except as provided in subsection (4), the applicant
